Why Log-Max LLR Needs a Noise Floor Estimate (The Scaling Trap)Your observation that LLRs are based on relative powers is entirely correct for choosing the most likely tone. If Tone 3 has 500 units of power and Tone 4 has 100 units, Tone 3 is clearly the winner for that symbol.However, the absolute scale of the LLR value matters immensely to the LDPC decoder. The log-max approximation for a bit \(b\) in a power-only (non-coherent) system is mathematically scaled by the noise variance (\(\sigma ^{2}\)):\(LLR\approx \frac{P_{\text{bit=1}}-P_{\text{bit=0}}}{2\sigma ^{2}}\)If you ignore the noise floor denominator (\(2\sigma^2\)) and just use the raw difference between the relative powers, your decoder will experience two main failure modes at the extremes:In High SNR (Strong Signals): The raw power differences (\(P_1 - P_0\)) are massive. Without dividing by noise, your LLR values become huge numbers (e.g., +4000 or -3000). The LDPC decoder treats these as absolute, unshakeable truths. If a brief burst of interference corrupts just one symbol, the decoder gets stuck because it cannot override that single, overly confident "lie."In Low SNR (Weak Signals): The raw power differences are tiny (e.g., 1.2 vs 1.1). Without dividing by a tiny noise variance, the LLR values stay close to zero. The LDPC decoder treats them all as completely unreliable guesses, runs out of its maximum allowed iterations, and gives up on decoding.By properly estimating and dividing by the local noise floor, you normalize the LLRs so that a weak signal's relative differences are scaled up into a range where the LDPC matrix can actually work its error-correction magic.
